\begin_layout Chapter
A brief summary of macroeconomic policy from 1930
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Macroeconomic policy in the early 20th century
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prior to the 1930's it is difficult to talk about 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

Macroeconomic policy
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 as such.
 Government spending was relatively low and concentrated on administration and defence.
 Taxes were raised to finance government spending,
 and,
 exceptionally,
 particularly during wartime,
 fiscal deficits were financed by the issue of bonds.
 Monetary policy was largely confined to moving interest rates occasionally in response to inflows or outflows of gold as most of the world was on the Gold Standard from the last quarter of the 19
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 century.
 The prevailing view among both academics and governments was that the economy was self regulating,
 and although fluctuations were observed with periods of both inflation and deflation,
 these were held to be self-correcting,
 with the gold standard providing stability for international trade.
 Prior to 1913 there was an unprecedented process of globalisation and a general belief that major wars would be impossible due to the economic and trade links between countries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The collapse of the 1930s and beginnings of macroeconomic policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fiscal management of demand can said to have begun (in a piecemeal fashion) with Roosevelt’s New Deal in the US which supported programs of public works to alleviate unemployment in the Great Depression.
 It was given a theoretical basis with the publication of Keynes’ 
\emph on
General Theory of Employment,
 Interest and Money
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Keynes36"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which together with the practical experience of the wartime management of the US and UK economies in the 1940’s,
 formed the basis for post-war macroeconomic management from 1945 to the mid 1970’s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The dominance of fiscal policy to 1970
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the late 1930’s,
 with the combination of the great depression and Keynes critique of orthodox classical economics,
 it was broadly accepted by policy makers that fiscal policy had a central role in the management of aggregate demand.
 This consensus began to break down in the 1960’s and it is probably fair to say that for most of the last forty years monetary policy (with a few exceptions) has been accepted as the only legitimate instrument for the management of demand,
 and thus inflation,
 in most countries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initial attempts to use monetary policy to manage demand in the late 1970s and early 1980s,
 used a crude (and ineffective) monetarist interpretation of the link between the ‘money supply’ and the price level,
 as a means to controlling inflation.
 Early attempts at monetary base control showed that the link between monetary aggregates and inflation was tenuous and unpredictable.
 However,
 the experience did demonstrate that sufficiently high interest rates could depress economic activity sufficiently to eventually eliminate inflation (particularly when combined with institutional changes to weaken workers bargaining power),
 although at the cost of high unemployment and lost output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although fiscal policy was the dominant instrument of macroeconomic management in the post-war period,
 it was supplemented by monetary policy,
 often in the form of direct controls on bank lending,
 or the conditions of consumer credit.
 In the period of fixed exchange rates until 1973,
 the interest rate was used more for managing foreign exchange flows,
 to maintain the fixed exchange rate,
 than to directly control inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effectiveness of fiscal policy (and wartime spending) in creating full employment led to the consensus that full employment should be one of the central objectives of economic policy in the vast majority of market economies.
 There were also instruments and models including the crude IS-LM framework,
 which (falsely) claimed to be a formal version of Keynes theoretical work,
 together with the apparently strong empirical inverse relationship between unemployment and inflation formalised as the Phillips Curve 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "phillips1958"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These instruments and models created the belief amongst macroeconomic policy makers that maintaining full employment was possible,
 and a relatively simple technical matter of fine-tuning fiscal policy to boost demand if unemployment were to rise and to reduce demand when inflation rose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The crisis of policy making in the 1970s
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 1945 until about 1970 macroeconomic management in OECD countries appeared to have achieved full employment with steady growth and low (but gradually increasing) inflation.
 During this period average inflation in the US,
 the UK,
 France,
 Germany and Japan was vv,
 
