\nospellcheck default
,
 ww,
 xx,
 respectively while unemployment rates were of the order of 3% - 4%.
 There is little doubt that this period was probably the most successful in terms of crisis-free,
 sustained positive macroeconomic results for most western industrialised countries that had ever been observed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strains in the system were however manifesting themselves.
 The policy focus was on maintaining full employment,
 but the Phillips curve trade-off which had been previous identified between the rate of unemployment and the level of inflation appeared to be breaking down,
 so that from the mid 1960’s inflation levels associated with a given level of unemployed resources was gradually rising.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover,
 the world financial system was effectively on a US dollar standard,
 with US dollars being the principal reserve currency for all other countries.
 Expansionary fiscal policy in the US,
 designed both to generated full employment and finance the Vietnam war,
 meant that there was effectively a surplus of dollars in the rest of the world.
 The anchor of the Bretton Woods world financial system was the dollar which had a value fixed,
 and was freely convertible to gold,
 held in reserve by the US Treasury.
 Differing fiscal policies and inflation rates among the large industrial economies,
 meant that disequilibria were transmitted into the balance of payments,
 with deficit countries under pressure to tighten policy in order to correct the external disequilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This pressure,
 however,
 did not apply to the US.
 Its balance of payments deficit (dollar surplus) simply translated into increases in dollar reserves held by other countries.
 This came to be known as the ‘exorbitant privilege’ of the US.
 The system could only be stable as long as the link between the dollar and gold was credible.
 From the mid sixties this credibility began to be tested by Central Banks,
 particularly in Europe,
 which began increasing,
 their holdings of gold,
 by exchanging dollars for gold.
 As US gold reserves diminished,
 it was clear that something would have to give.
 In the end the US simply suspended the convertibility of dollars to gold,
 thus effectively ending the Bretton Woods system and ushering in the system of floating exchange rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Acceleration of inflation in the 1970s
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1971 was followed very quickly by a sharp increase in world commodity prices (particularly oil which quadrupled in price in 1973 and further tripled in price from 1979 to 1981).
 These price increases came on top of an inflation rate which had gradually increased in the previous decades.
 The result was that inflation increased rapidly,
 peaking in 1974 or 1975 in most countries as the external supply shock fed into domestic inflation.
 Policy responses were varied and often incoherent.
 In the UK for example,
 in 1973 fiscal policy became more expansionary,
 while subsequent inflation was dealt with by an (ineffective) wage control policy which quickly broke down.
 In the US the break with Bretton Woods was also combined with the announcement of a wage and price freeze.
 In most cases direct controls on wages and prices proved to be at best temporary palliatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The difficult political economy of fiscal policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While fiscal policy could potentially be very effective for the management of aggregate demand from a technical perspective,
 the political economy of fiscal management proved to be too complex,
 in the sense that increases in expenditure (or reductions in taxation) to stimulate growth or offset an increase in unemployment were politically very difficult to reverse once the economy began to overheat.
 Thus,
 in practice,
 building in a bias towards expansionary fiscal policy which would only be confronted once a crisis was generated through accelerating inflation and/or a balance of payments collapse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The dominance of monetary policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This led to the development of a consensus from the late 1980’s that the only appropriate instrument to regulate demand was monetary policy (focused particularly on the use of short term interest rates to influence the entire yield curve through expectations),
 while fiscal policy was relegated to service delivery and maintaining a ‘sustainable’ debt burden.
 By the 1990’s,
 in many countries,
 this became formalised in the form of inflation targeting regimes,
 managed by independent Central Banks.
 This historical evolution is described in detail in the UK Treasury’s semi-official account of macroeconomic policy making 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "balls2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and in the US by Ben Bernanke’s analysis of monetary policy (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bernanke2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Theoretical and historical origins of monetarism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Behind the rise of monetary policy as the dominant macroeconomic policy instrument was the fundamental notion that relative prices were determined only by 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

real factors
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 (technology and preferences) from the solution of innumerable optimisation problems by individual agents resulting in a vector of 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

objective
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 equilibrium prices,
 while the price level was determined by the ‘money supply’ (the ‘Classical dichotomy’).
 Although never demonstrated empirically,
 the ‘Classical Dichotomy’ became as central to macroeconomic thought as it had been in the 19th and early 20th centuries,
 and indeed has been highly influential in theoretical and policy discussions up to the present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This view relies upon the idea that ‘money’ as a means of exchange can be clearly distinguished from other financial assets which constitute a store of future purchasing power.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is the existence of this wide range of financial assets which often led to endless and ultimately futile debates on the correct definition of ‘money’ for the purposes of controlling the money supply and thus inflation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The idea that ‘money’ (as opposed to other financial assets) has no utility in itself and is simply held for transactions purposes is the central assumption of the reformulation of the doctrine of monetarism by Milton Friedman in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "friedman1956,friedman1969"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (both reprinted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Friedman06"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the idea that the money supply (however defined) is a principal determinant of the price level dates back at least to the eighteenth century,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See,
 for example,
 the work of David Hume
\end_layout

\end_inset

 it was articulated in its modern form in the 1950s by Milton Friedman.
 Friedman argued strongly that excessive growth of the money supply was the only cause of inflation,
 and that in policy terms the only solution to excessive price growth was to restrain the growth of the 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

money supply’.
 In the 1950’s and most of the 1960’s monetarism was treated as a fringe doctrine which could not challenge the prevailing dominance of fiscal policy and the Keynesian orthodoxy of the time.
 However,
 by the end of the 1960’s,
 it began to gain in credibility in academic circles,
 as it became clear that fiscal policy was apparently unable to stabilise the economy and ensure full employment with low inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the 1970’s monetarism gradually became the orthodoxy for macroeconomic policy making,
 almost by default,
 as the combination of rising inflation with economic stagnation and rising unemployment appeared to be intractable using the traditional instruments of fiscal policy,
 sometimes combined with wage and price controls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Monetarism appeared to both provide a shortcut to the control of inflation,
 as well as an ideological framework for a reduction of state intervention in the economy.
 It began to be adopted in a soft form in the UK following the balance of payments crisis of 1976 and in a much more ideologically pure fashion with election of Margaret Thatcher as Prime Minister in 1979 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lankester2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a detailed account of the UK experience).
 In the US monetarism as a policy doctrine came to the fore with the appointment of Paul Volker as Chairman of the Federal Reserve in 1979 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bernanke2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Monetarism in practice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With its ascendancy in the UK and the US quickly began to dominate economic policy making and theorising in most OECD countries and,
 as a result of its diffusion through multilateral financial institutions,
 and their regional equivalents,
 to much of the developing world.
 The appeal of monetarism was not simply the apparent simplicity of its policy recommendations (controlling the money supply in order to control inflation),
 but also that it provided a theoretical basis for concepts such as the ‘Natural Rate of Unemployment’
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Friedman68"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (or as it was later called,
 the ‘Non-Accelerating Inflation Rate of Unemployment’).
 This concept provided a rationale for arguing that the government had no role in trying to regulate the level of unemployment,
 since it would automatically move to its natural rate which Friedman argued would be the level:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ground out by the Walrasian system of general equilibrium equations,
 provided there is embedded in them the actual structural characteristics of the labor and commodity markets,
 including market imperfections,
 stochastic variability in demands and supplies,
 the cost of gathering information about job vacancies and labor availabilities,
 the costs of mobility,
 and so on.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
